North Korea says it will "in no way" dismantle unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that ongoing sanctions were deepening its lack of trust in the United States and that there was no way the country would unilaterally leave its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and vowing not to proliferate nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
"Without any confidence in the United States there will be no confidence in our national security and under such circumstances in no way will we unilaterally dismantle ourselves first."
While Ri reiterated familiar complaints from North Korea about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization in which North Korea would have been rewarded as it took steps gradually, his statement appeared significantly that it did not refuse the pass-Pong-Pyong denuclearization as unilaterally without consideration.
He referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a U.S. president serving his duties and a leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12, when Kim vowed to work towards the "denuclearisation of the Korean peninsula."
North Korea was seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first surrender its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to reduce tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a coherent way, and even objects to the "declaration of an end to war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can break us is a dream of people who don't know about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions are deepening our lack of trust."
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party to this issue of denuclearisation were South Korea and not the United States it would have been like this denuclearization of the penis."
Despite this, the tone of Ri's speech was dramatically different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's rocket-propelled U.S. mainland was inevitable after Mr. President Trump called Kim's "successful mission" a "man-of-the-master."
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to dismantle, but said much work remained to be done and sanctions should remain in place until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this, saying "if it takes two, three years or five months - it doesn't make a difference."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
