Harvard students take a course on taking enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has managed to get all of its undergraduates to sleep more with the aim of fighting the growing Macho culture of studying all night and staying awake thanks to coffee.
Academics have found that university students in first place in the world often do not have an idea of the basic real things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after making a speech about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"A girl came to me last time and said, 'Why are they telling me this now, in my last year?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which started for the first time this year, explains to students the essential things about how good sleep traditions help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding the students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a student's bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, trainers and books to tell them about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance will have an effect from sleep deficiency, and the importance of routine sleep.
In another section, participants are told how long-term insomnia can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know - as much as you have a right to know the health effects when choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of being proud that "you managed to stay up all night studying" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students meant that insomnia was a growing problem.
Ensuring that you sleep enough, and of good quality, should be a student's "secret weapon" to fight stress, intense fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the mind in a hunger-making mode.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California, who is studying chemistry and physics biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having attended one of his classes last year during his first year in Harvard.
He said that the course opened his eyes and inspired him to insist on a course throughout the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduated students to do a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students should consider making an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can unbalance your circadian rhythm, and lead to trouble sleeping.
